Tables_Styles

 

Applying or changing a style class

 

 Click on the element, select Table Class and select Create Style Class – Launches Create Style Dialog – Then open the CSS Editor

 

 Click on the element, select Table Class and select Edit Style Class – Opens the CSS Editor with the style/class selected

 

 Click on the element, select Table Class and select Reset Style Class – Removes the class applied to the element

 

 Click on the element, select Table Class and select a style from the Style Class list

 

 Selecting the element and applying (reset class) from the Style Drop-down on the formatting toolbar

 

 Selecting the element and applying a style from the Style Drop-down on the formatting toolbar

 

 Verify that Classes applied to the element render correctly in the Editor and all outputs
 

Create Style Dialog – Launched from a Table object.

 

 Dialog title is correct

 

 Spelling and grammar are correct

 

 No duplicate accelerators

 

 All accelerators function
  Tab order is correct (forward and reverse orders)
  Keyboard can navigate and change settings
  Dialog is easy to use and understand

 

 F1 and “?” function and the content is correct
  Boundary test all controls
  Negative numbers
  Large number
  Text
  Various characters and symbols (Inc. international)
  The “default” active button should make sense
  Default options are displayed in the screenshot
  Cancel, Esc, Red ‘X’ and ALT+F4 close the dialog without change
  OK and Enter close dialog with changes
  Dialog is resizable and redraws correctly
  Dialog remembers setting and sizes from previous session

 

 Dialog opens correctly on a dual monitor system

 

 Clicking the icon in the upper left corner displays options:

 

 Restore, Move, Size, Min., Max., Close – All work

 

 Restore, Min., Max are disabled
 

UI Controls

 

 Name: Name of the class (If left blank, changes will be made to the element's main style)

 

 Comment: Lets you add a comment to the style class.

 

 Properties for the New Class: All columns should be sortable and not resizable.

 

 Columns

 

 Include: Allows for the selection of specific properties to include or exclude from the new style or style update

 

 Property: Displays the CSS property of the class to be updated

 

 Value: Displays the value of the property to be updated
  Select Stylesheet to modify: Allows for the selection of the stylesheet to which the new class/style will be added. If the topic is associated with multiple stylesheets, this column should be sortable.
  Create style and update the source element: Creates the style/class and applies it to the selected element

 

 Create style without updating the source element: Creates the style/class but doesn’t apply it to the selected element
   
 

Test Cases
  Type invalid text, numbers, character, etc into fields that will take user input
  Type extra long input into fields
  Type characters and symbols into fields
  Attempt to create a duplicate style class
  Be sure that any error dialogs that are displayed from this dialog are in written plain English
  Verify that all properties get written to the correct style/class in the correct stylesheet.
  Test with multiple stylesheets
  Stylesheet and Styles:
 

Test:
  creating a new class for Tables
  copying and pasting the Table node and the ‘NewClass’ node
  Deleting the Table and Class nodes of Table
